Five truths about terrorism
SAO PAULO – American policy is being held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the country's top problem – a 3% increase in a month.
Over the past ten years, never have so many Americans been this concerned about terrorism, even though the number is still far below the 46% recorded the day after the 9/11 attacks in 2001.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion were most felt during the Republican primary election for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly inflammatory (if not incendiary), has undoubtedly benefited from this.
Certain politicians dare to speak of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War".
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
However, presidential candidates, as well as some media outlets that follow the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads", have exaggerated the proportions.
To put terrorism into its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
Terrorists care more about retaining attention and monopolizing political news than the number of their victims themselves.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care of its staging.
The barbaric beheadings broadcast on social media are meant to destabilize and scandalize – and thus monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every terrorist action is playing the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the most severe threat to the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills much less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be assassinated by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (a probability of one in 950,000), from an accident caused by a household appliance (a probability of one in 1.5 million), from a deer or elk crossing the road (a probability of one in 2 million), or in a commercial airliner crash (a probability of one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year driving while texting or talking on their mobile phones.
This is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks perpetrated by disgruntled employees or mass shootings in universities or schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist flare-up.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
In the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, originating from the "autonomous" left, hijacked planes across national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon dressed up in a religious costume.
Many of their leaders are not traditional fundamentalists, but people with a destroyed identity by globalization, who seek meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of EI limits its sphere of attraction.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
EI will ultimately be defeated, just like the transnational terrorism that preceded it.
Terrorism is like jiu-jitsu.
The weakest of the two adversaries uses the power of the strongest to defeat it.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have succeeded in overthrowing one.
But if they succeed in shocking and provoking enough citizens of a state to push them to futile actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaida managed to draw Americans to Afghanistan.
The EI was born in the ruins of the US-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, we need smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the power of influence (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Soft power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and counter the recruitment efforts of extremists.
That's why attention to the narrative of events and how the United States' actions are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision airstrikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the goodwill that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some of the current presidential candidates is so counter-productive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It is an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let's not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and hoodlums take place.
If we leave the big stage of public discourse to them, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and betray our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
